### MeshTransmissionMaterial

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

To optimize performance when multiple materials rendering the scene individually becomes too costly, you can share a buffer texture. One method is to enable `transmissionSampler`. This utilizes the internal buffer used by MeshPhysicalMaterials, which can be faster. The trade-off is that transmissive materials using this sampler will not be able to "see" other transparent or transmissive objects. Alternatively, you can manually provide a texture to the `buffer` prop, for example, by using `useFBO`. This gives you more control over the buffer and its resolution, allowing for custom rendering setups.

--------------------------------

### MeshTransmissionMaterial

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/drei/blob/master/docs/shaders/mesh-transmission-material.mdx

By manually providing a buffer texture using `useFBO`, you can achieve a setup where multiple meshes share the same rendering buffer. This is useful for complex scenes where consistent reflections and refractions are desired across several objects. The example demonstrates how to create a buffer, render the scene into it, and then apply that buffer's texture to multiple `MeshTransmissionMaterial` instances. This approach allows for shared rendering resources, potentially improving performance and ensuring visual coherence.

